{"id":"seward-highway","generatedAt":"2026-07-11T07:11:33.093Z","designation":"All-American Road","parkCode":null,"source":{"roadArticle":"Seward Highway","revisionId":1355388070,"url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Seward_Highway"},"attribution":{"license":"CC BY-SA 4.0","licenseUrl":"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/","articleUrl":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Seward_Highway","text":"Route, junction, and history details adapted from the Wikipedia article \"Seward Highway\", by Wikipedia contributors, licensed under CC BY-SA 4.0."},"sources":[{"name":"Wikipedia","src":"wikipedia","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Seward_Highway","revisionId":1355388070,"retrievedAt":"2026-07-11T07:11:33.093Z"},{"name":"Federal Highway Administration — National Scenic Byways","src":"fhwa","url":"https://www.fhwa.dot.gov/byways","retrievedAt":"2026-07-11T07:11:33.093Z"},{"name":"OpenStreetMap contributors (ODbL)","src":"osm","url":"https://www.openstreetmap.org/copyright","retrievedAt":"2026-07-11T07:11:33.093Z"}],"endpoints":{"from":"Seward, AK","to":"Municipality of Anchorage, AK","via":["Bear Creek, AK","Primrose, AK","Moose Pass, AK"]},"itinerary":[{"seq":1,"place":"Seward","state":"AK","kind":"terminus","mileFromStart":0,"toNextMi":3.3,"note":"The drive begins here","control":["Railway Avenue","A Street","Port Avenue"],"lat":60.11491,"lng":-149.44209,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":2,"place":"Bear Creek","state":"AK","kind":"town","mileFromStart":3.3,"toNextMi":13.7,"note":"Junction toward Nash Road","control":["Nash Road","Herman Leirer Road(formerly Exit Glacier Road)","Bear Lake Road"],"lat":60.17704,"lng":-149.39772,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":3,"place":"Primrose","state":"AK","kind":"town","mileFromStart":17,"toNextMi":11.8,"note":"Junction toward Primrose Spur Road","control":["Primrose Spur Road"],"lat":60.34261,"lng":-149.34557,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":4,"place":"Moose Pass","state":"AK","kind":"crossing","mileFromStart":28.8,"toNextMi":16.6,"note":"Junction toward Depot Road","control":["Depot Road","Southern trailhead","Johnson Pass Trail","AK-1 (Sterling Highway) AK-9 south"],"lat":60.48752,"lng":-149.3708,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":5,"place":"Summit Lake","state":"AK","kind":"crossing","mileFromStart":45.4,"toNextMi":22.1,"note":"Junction toward Summit Lake Lodge","control":["Summit Lake Lodge"],"lat":60.63353,"lng":-149.51061,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":6,"place":"Turnagain Pass","state":"AK","kind":"crossing","mileFromStart":67.5,"toNextMi":10.5,"note":"Crosses Turnagain Pass","control":["Turnagain Pass—highway divides"],"lat":60.78009,"lng":-149.43359,"src":"wikipedia","snapped":true},{"seq":7,"place":"Municipality of Anchorage","state":"AK","kind":"terminus","mileFromStart":78,"toNextMi":null,"note":"The drive ends here","control":["Portage Glacier Highway","Alaska Railroad Portage siding","Alyeska Highway to Crow Creek Road","Sawmill Road","Indian Road","McHugh Creek Campground Road","Potter Valley Road","South end of freeway","Old Seward HighwayRabbit Creek Road","De Armoun Road","Huffman Road","O'Malley Road","Minnesota Drive","East Dimond BoulevardAbbott Road","East 76th AvenueLore Road","East Dowling Road","East Tudor Road","East 36th Avenue","East Benson Boulevard","East Northern Lights Boulevard","East Fireweed Lane","AK-1 north (Gambell Street","Ingra Street)","East 20th Avenue"],"lat":60.77698,"lng":-149.22262,"src":"wikipedia"}],"history":{"paragraphs":["An 18-mile-long (29 km) stretch of the Seward Highway, traveling from Seward to Kenai Lake was completed in 1923. Another segment of the highway, running between Moose Pass and Hope, was completed in 1937. The Mile 18 bridge, nicknamed \"The Missing Link\", which would connect the Seward and Moose Pass portions, was not completed until 1946, which was a major cause of the delayed completion of the highway. The roadway was completed on October 19, 1951, connecting Seward to the major city of Anchorage by road for the first time (Seward was previously reached by sea, rail, or air). The entire length of the highway was paved in 1952. During the 1964 Alaska earthquake, about 20 miles (32 km) of the Seward Highway sank below the high water mark of Turnagain Arm; the highway and its bridges were raised and rebuilt in 1964–66.","The highway was designated a National Forest Scenic Byway by the United States Forest Service on September 8, 1989. Later, the State of Alaska added it to the State Scenic Byway system on January 29, 1993. The final designation was added on June 15, 2000, when the Seward Highway was named an All-American Road as part of the National Scenic Byway program by the United States Secretary of Transportation. The length of the highway traveling from the AK-1 and AK-9 intersection to the northern terminus is designated as Interstate A-3 by the National Highway System.","In July 2016, Alaska DOT&PF officials posted updated speed limits on a five-mile (8.0 km) section of the Seward Highway south of Anchorage between Hope Junction to the top of Turnagain Pass. The limit in the right lane is 55 mph (89 km/h), while that in the left lane is 65 mph (105 km/h). The project is designed to enhance safety and improve congestion by enforcing passing lane usage.","In 2017, Alaska DOT&PF announced a four-year Milepost 75–90 Rehabilitation Project, scheduled to begin in 2018, to make major safety improvements to a busy crash-prone section of the Seward Highway from Girdwood to beyond the Portage curve toward Turnagain Pass ending at Ingram Creek. In July 2015 a tour bus crash at milepost 79 killed one man and critically injured several others, causing a 10-hour traffic jam. During the summer months, up to 15,000 vehicles use this 15-mile (24 km) stretch of Seward Highway daily."],"sourceSection":"History","src":"wikipedia"},"highlights":[{"n":"Seward","d":"The drive begins here","q":"Seward","lat":60.12444444,"lng":-149.43333333,"src":"wikipedia"},{"n":"Moose Pass","d":"Junction toward Depot Road","q":"Moose Pass","lat":60.48777778,"lng":-149.37083333,"src":"wikipedia"},{"n":"Summit Lake","d":"Junction toward Summit Lake Lodge","q":"Summit Lake","lat":60.6322475,"lng":-149.5069536,"src":"wikipedia"},{"n":"Turnagain Pass","d":"Crosses Turnagain Pass","q":"Turnagain Pass","lat":61.21666667,"lng":-149.89361111,"src":"wikipedia"},{"n":"Municipality of Anchorage","d":"The drive ends here","q":"Municipality of Anchorage","lat":61.21666667,"lng":-149.89361111,"src":"wikipedia"}],"references":[{"n":1,"text":"Seward Historic Preservation Commission. \"Community History and Character\". City of Seward. Archived from the original on February 8, 2012. Retrieved March 13, 2012.","url":"https://web.archive.org/web/20120208093015/http://www.cityofseward.net/hpc/seward_history/index.html"},{"n":2,"text":"Witt, Jennifer W. (2010). Annual Traffic Volume Report (PDF) (Report) (2008–2009–2010 ed.). Alaska Department of Transportation & Public Facilities. pp. III-30 – III-31, III-35 – III-37. Archived from the original (PDF) on March 30, 2014. Retrieved March 15, 2012.","url":"https://web.archive.org/web/20140330090745/http://www.dot.state.ak.us/stwdplng/mapping/trafficmaps/trafficdata_reports_cen/2010_ATVR_FINAL_All_Posted.pdf"},{"n":3,"text":"Federal Highway Administration (March 2004). National Highway System: Alaska (PDF) (Map). Federal Highway Administration. Archived from the original (PDF) on October 16, 2008. Retrieved March 15, 2012.","url":"https://web.archive.org/web/20081016224724/http://www.fhwa.dot.gov/planning/nhs/maps/ak/ak_alaska.pdf"},{"n":4,"text":"Weingroff, Richard F. (April 7, 2011). \"Interstates in Hawaii: Are We Crazy???\". Ask the Rambler. Federal Highway Administration. Retrieved March 15, 2011.","url":"https://highways.dot.gov/highway-history/general-highway-history/rambler/ask-rambler-interstates-hawaii-are-we-crazy"},{"n":5,"text":"United States Congress (1994). \"Title 23, Chapter 1, Section 103\". United States Code. United States Government Publishing Office. Retrieved 